<subSubSection id="CCFD0CC3FFFB0147600EF60A90AF8DE3" pageId="25" pageNumber="48" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="84585F48FFFB0147600EF60A90AF8DE3" blockId="25.[828,1437,1546,1729]" pageId="25" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis id="B693835AFFFB0147600EF60A90CE8D03" bold="true" box="[828,959,1546,1569]" pageId="25" pageNumber="48">Comments.</emphasis>
I examined only photographs of the 
<typeStatus id="5B5CE1EAFFFB01476651F60A901B8D63" pageId="25" pageNumber="48">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="43E724CBFFFB014760A7F62A97018D63" authorityName="Medvedev" authorityYear="2001" box="[917,1136,1578,1601]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyxantha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costata">
<emphasis id="B693835AFFFB014760A7F62A97018D63" box="[917,1136,1578,1601]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="48">Platyxantha costata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Based on the structure of the aedeagus with a bifurcate apex I tentatively transfer it to 
<taxonomicName id="43E724CBFFFB0147605DF66A90958DA3" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1865" box="[879,996,1642,1665]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Hyphaenia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B693835AFFFB0147605DF66A90958DA3" box="[879,996,1642,1665]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="48">Hyphaenia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as was speculated by 
<bibRefCitation id="E07622B9FFFB014767EFF66A96ED8DA3" author="MEDVEDEV L. N." box="[1245,1436,1642,1665]" firstAuthor="MEDVEDEV" journalOrPublisher="Entomologica Basiliensia" pageId="25" pageNumber="48" pagination="159 - 191" part="23" refId="ref32264" refString="MEDVEDEV L. N. 2001: Chrysomelidae of southern Asia (Coleoptera). Entomologica Basiliensia 23: 159 - 191." title="Chrysomelidae of southern Asia (Coleoptera)" type="journal article" year="2001">MEDVEDEV (2001)</bibRefCitation>
himself, however, further study is necessary to confirm this placement.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
